  "text": "The PromQL query parsing and validation pipeline in github.com/prometheus/prometheus is implemented across several key packages and files:\n\n**Parser Interface and Implementation** (promql/parser/parse.go):\nThe Parser interface (line 52) defines the public API with methods like ParseExpr, ParseMetric, ParseMetricSelector, and ParseSeriesDesc. The concrete implementation is provided by promQLParser struct (line 61), and internally uses a parser struct (line 143) that manages the parsing state. The parseExpr method initializes parsing, and then delegates to the generated parser via parseGenerated.\n\n**Lexer Tokenizer** (promql/parser/lex.go):\nThe Lexer struct (line 276) performs lexical analysis by scanning the input string and emitting tokens as Item structs (line 26). ItemType (line 101) is an enumeration of all token types including operators, keywords, aggregators, and identifiers. The Lexer maintains scanning state and provides methods like NextItem and backup for token management.\n\n**AST Node Type Definitions** (promql/parser/ast.go):\nThe AST is defined through the Node interface (line 38) and its specialized Expr interface (line 77) for expressions. Expression types include: VectorSelector (line 206) for metric selection with label matchers, BinaryExpr (line 101) for binary operations (arithmetic, comparison, set operations), Call (line 124) for function calls, AggregateExpr (line 91) for aggregation functions, MatrixSelector (line 132) for range vectors, SubqueryExpr (line 142) for subqueries, UnaryExpr (line 185) for unary operations, ParenExpr (line 172) for parenthesized expressions, NumberLiteral (line 163) and StringLiteral (line 178) for literals, StepInvariantExpr (line 195) for optimization, and DurationExpr (line 114) for duration expressions. Each expression type implements the Expr interface to provide Type() and PromQLExpr() methods.\n\n**Generated Yacc Parser** (promql/parser/generated_parser.y and generated_parser.y.go):\nThe yacc grammar file (generated_parser.y) defines the PromQL syntax using production rules. It generates the yacc parser at promql/parser/generated_parser.y.go (line 1 indicates it's code-generated by goyacc). The yyParserImpl struct handles the actual parsing state machine, converting the token stream from the lexer into an AST.\n\n**Function Registry** (promql/parser/functions.go):\nThe Function struct (line 18) defines function metadata including Name, ArgTypes (list of ValueType parameters), Variadic flag, ReturnType, and Experimental flag. The Functions map (line 27) is the registry containing all supported PromQL functions like abs, absent, avg_over_time, ceil, etc., with their signatures and return types. This allows the parser to validate function calls during AST construction.\n\n**Value Type System** (promql/parser/value.go):\nThe Value interface (line 17) represents values returned from query evaluation. ValueType (line 23) is a type-safe enumeration of all value types: ValueTypeNone, ValueTypeVector (instant vectors), ValueTypeScalar, ValueTypeMatrix (range vectors), and ValueTypeString. Each AST node has a Type() method that returns its ValueType, enabling compile-time type validation.\n\n**Type Validation** (promql/parser/parse.go):\nThe checkAST method (line 720) performs semantic validation and type checking on the parsed AST. It recursively validates each node, ensures proper operand types for operators, validates function arguments against their signatures, and checks aggregation modifier validity. Function types are resolved from the Functions registry, and type mismatches are recorded as parse errors.\n\n**Engine Integration** (promql/engine.go):\nThe Engine struct integrates the parser into the query execution pipeline. It provides NewInstantQuery and NewRangeQuery methods (interfaces defined at line 125-127) that parse query strings using the parser, then execute the resulting AST against the time-series database. The Query interface (line 143) represents an executable query and provides the Statement() method to access the parsed AST.\n\n**Function Implementations** (promql/functions.go):\nBeyond the registry metadata in promql/parser/functions.go, the actual function implementations are in promql/functions.go, which contains evaluator functions for each PromQL function and special function registries like AnchoredSafeFunctions, SmoothedSafeFunctions, and AtModifierUnsafeFunctions that restrict modifier usage.\n\nThe complete pipeline: Query String → Lexer (tokenization) → Generated Yacc Parser (syntax analysis) → AST Construction → checkAST (semantic validation & type checking) → Execution Engine with the validated AST."
